subsection.p:
 			For many substances, under normal conditions, specific heat is nearly independent of temperature over the temperature range under study.  Therefore, you can deduce a formula for heat Q  needed when a substance of mass  M is heated so that its temperature rises from  T_1 to T_2.

				 \amp Q = M c_P \left(T_2-T_1 \right)  \ \ \text{(constant }p \text{ process)}
				 \amp Q = M c_V \left(T_2-T_1 \right)  \ \ \text{(constant }V \text{ process)}

 			Often specific heat is a function of temperature, c(T). In that case, to obtain heat needed for a finite change in temperature, we plot  M\,c versus  T and compute the area under the curve.   

				 \amp Q = \text{Area under }M\,c_P \text{ vs }T  \ \ \text{(constant }p \text{ process)}
				 \amp Q = \text{Area under }M\,c_V \text{ vs }T  \ \ \text{(constant }V \text{ process)}
